    "answers": [{
        "owner": {
            "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/zflGZ.png?s=256",
            "account_id": 440158,
            "user_type": "registered",
            "user_id": 829571,
            "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/829571/assylias",
            "reputation": 330070,
            "display_name": "assylias",
            "accept_rate": 94
        },
        "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
        "score": 3,
        "is_accepted": true,
        "last_activity_date": 1401893785,
        "creation_date": 1401893785,
        "body": "<p>In the context of class declaration, and according to the <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-8.html#jls-8.1.1\" rel=\"nofollow\">JLS #8.1.1<\/a>, these are all class modifiers.<\/p>\n\n<p>And if you read a bit further you will see that only public, private and protected are access modifiers (which makes sense: they determine whether the class is accessible or not from other parts of the code).<\/p>\n\n<p>So yes, technically, abstract and final are not access modifiers and the error message could be more precise. Note that javac (Java 8) error message is:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>illegal combination of modifiers: abstract and final<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n",
        "answer_id": 24040856,
        "question_id": 24040700
    }],
